1983 North American Soccer League season| ]]\n[[Category:Tulsa Roughnecks matches|1983]]\n[[Category:Toronto Blizzard matches]]\n[[Category:Sport in Vancouver]]\n[[Category:1983 in British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Vancouver]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox football match\n|                   title = Soccer Bowl '83\n|            other_titles =\n|                   image = [[File:Soccer Bowl '83 logo.png|x150px]]\n|                   event = [[Soccer Bowl]]\n|                   team1 = [[Tulsa Roughnecks (1978\u201384)|Tulsa Roughnecks]]\n|        team1association =\n|              team1score = 2\n|                   team2 = [[Toronto Blizzard (1971\u201384)|Toronto Blizzard]]\n|        team2association = \n|              team2score = 0\n|                 details = \n|                    date = {{Start date|1983|10|01}}\n|                 stadium = [[BC Place Stadium]]\n|                    city = [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]]\n|      man_of_the_match1a = [[Njego Pesa]]\n| man_of_the_match1atitle = \n|      man_of_the_match1b = \n| man_of_the_match1btitle = \n|            fair_player1 = \n|       fair_player1title = \n|                 referee = Ed Bellion ([[United States Soccer Federation|USA]])\n|              attendance = 53,326\n|                 weather =\n|                  anthem =\n|                halftime = \n|                 network = [[USA Network|USA]], [[CTV Television Network|CTV]]\n|              announcers = \n|                network2 = \n|             announcers2 =\n|                network3 =\n|             announcers3 =\n|                previous = [[Soccer Bowl '82|1982]]\n|                    next = [[Soccer Bowl '84|1984]]\n}}\n\n'''[[Soccer Bowl]] '83''' was the championship final of the [[1983 North American Soccer League season|1983 NASL season]]. The match was played on October 1, 1983 at [[BC Place Stadium]] in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], between the [[Tulsa Roughnecks (1978\u201384)|Tulsa Roughnecks]] and the [[Toronto Blizzard (1971\u201384)|Toronto Blizzard]]. The Roughnecks won the match, 2\u20130, to claim their first championship.<ref>{{cite web|last=NASL|title=NASLSoccerBowl - History - Past Winner|url=http://www.naslsoccerbowl.com/index.php?id=788|publisher=North American Soccer League}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=NASL|title=NASL 1968-1984 - Yearly Result|url=http://www.nasl.com/index.php?id=458|publisher=North American Soccer League}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe Tulsa Roughnecks won the Southern Division with a 17-13 record and a total of 145 points. They dispatched the [[Fort Lauderdale Strikers (1977\u201383)|Fort Lauderdale Strikers]] in the quarterfinals with a two-game sweep. By virtue of their two games to one victory In the semifinals against the [[Montreal Manic]], the Roughnecks advanced to the Soccer Bowl for the first time in franchise history.\n\nThe Toronto Blizzard qualified for the playoffs as a wild card by finishing third in the Eastern Division with a 16-14 record and a total of 135 points. In the quarterfinals they were the upset-winner over the Western Division champion [[Vancouver Whitecaps (1974\u201384)|Vancouver Whitecaps]] by two games to one. Vancouver had only lost 6 matches all season. The Blizzard pulled off a second upset in their semifinal match-up by sweeping the [[Golden Bay Earthquakes]] in two games, and earning their second ever trip to the Soccer Bowl.\n\n===Pre-match controversy===\nDuring game three of their semifinal series with Montreal, Tulsa forward [[Ron Futcher]] picked up his third yellow card of the playoffs. By rule this earned him a one-match suspension, and league director of operations [[Ted Howard (soccer)|Ted Howard]] was poised to enforce it. For his part, Futcher was not only the team's leading scorer, but also a leader in the Roughnecks' locker room. Tulsa's owners appealed the yellow card and even alluded to the press, the possibility of boycotting the final if Futcher was not allowed to play. Toronto team president [[Clive Toye]] felt that bending the rules for a star player might set a bad precedent, but was nevertheless prepared to face whatever lineup Tulsa put on the pitch. Ultimately, NASL president [[Howard J. Samuels]] overruled Ted Howard and decided to allow Futcher to play, because he felt that the fans in attendance would be the ones made to suffer by Futcher's absence.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stinson |first=Dan|title=Samuels allows Futcher to play |date=October 1, 1983|publisher=[[Vancouver Sun]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/494531694 |page=B1 |accessdate=December 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Soccer |date=October 1, 1983|publisher=Chicago Tribune|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/387946656/?terms=Samuels%2Ballows |page=Sec.2; 5 |accessdate=December 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Game summary==\n\n===Championship results===\n{{football box\n|date = October 1<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=C7NOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=rPsDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2121,402889&dq=soccer+bowl&hl=en|title=Lakeland Ledger - Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com}}</ref>\n|time = 16:00 ([[Pacific Time Zone|PDT]])<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/558386266/?terms=Soccer%2BBowl|date=October 1, 1983|accessdate=November 29, 2019|newspaper=Red Deer Advocate|title=Goaltenders in spotlight in NASL Championship|page=9B}}</ref>\n|team1 = [[Tulsa Roughnecks (1978\u201384)|Tulsa Roughnecks]]\n|score = 2\u20130\n|report = \n|team2 = [[Toronto Blizzard (NASL)|Toronto Blizzard]]\n|goals1 = [[Njego Pesa|Pesa]] {{goal|55:36|Wallace, Danaeifard}}<br> [[Ron Futcher|Futcher]] {{goal|61:37|Wallace, Moore}}\n|goals2 = \n|stadium = [[BC Place Stadium]], [[Vancouver]]\n|attendance = 53,326<ref>http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1121360/2/index.htm</ref>\n|referee = Ed Bellion<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105045420/http://www.naslsoccerbowl.com/index.php?id=788|title=Pa